{
  "query": "In a zoo environment, what are the documented effects of altering the timing and predictability of feeding schedules for captive primates and carnivores?",
  "relevant_summary": "For captive primates, one replicated, controlled study in the USA found that when chimpanzees were fed on unpredictable schedules, inactivity decreased (Action 1338). Additionally, two before-and-after studies in Japan and the USA found that when the number of feeds per day were increased, the amount of time spent feeding increased in chimpanzees, but hair eating also increased in baboons (Action 1337).\n\nFor captive carnivores, multiple studies have documented effects of unpredictable feeding schedules. Three replicated, before-and-after studies in Switzerland, Ireland and Canada, UK, Ireland, Namibia and South Africa and one replicated, controlled study in Ireland found that an unpredictable feeding schedule reduced the frequency of stereotypic pacing behaviours in tigers and cheetahs (Action 1904). One replicated, before-and-after controlled study in the USA found that an unpredictable feeding schedule increased territorial behaviour in coyotes but did not affect travelling or foraging (Action 1904). Two before-and-after studies in Switzerland and the USA found that an unpredictable feeding schedule increased behavioural diversity in red foxes and alertness in a black-footed cat (Action 1904). However, one replicated, before-and-after study in the UK found that large felids fed once every three days paced more frequently on non-feeding days (Action 1906).",
